00:03:22.069 --> 00:03:27.789
If you have blue eyes, your eyes aren't actually
blue, in the sense that the molecules inside

00:03:27.789 --> 00:03:32.629
them are absorbing all other wavelengths of
visible light and diffusing the blue. No,

00:03:32.629 --> 00:03:39.880
no, no, instead, your eyes are blue for the
same reason that the sky is blue: interference.

00:03:39.880 --> 00:03:44.980
In our sky, light from the Sun encounters
molecules of air and because of the size

00:03:44.989 --> 00:03:51.069
of those molecules, light of longer wavelengths
can slip on by, but shorter wavelengths crash

00:03:51.069 --> 00:03:56.149
into the particles, like blue light, and scatter,
which is why we see blue when we look at the

00:03:56.149 --> 00:03:58.349
sky away from the Sun.

00:03:58.620 --> 00:04:04.700
Without the air molecules, that space would
just be black. And when direct sunlight has

00:04:04.700 --> 00:04:09.499
to travel through a lot of air, almost all
of the colors get scattered out except for

00:04:09.499 --> 00:04:16.039
the longest wavelengths, the red, which is
what gives a sunrise and a sunset their color.

00:04:16.040 --> 00:04:22.220
The iris of your eyeball contains a hazy layer
where light can be scattered just like the

00:04:22.220 --> 00:04:27.830
sky. Through a similar, but slightly different
process, shorter wavelengths are scattered

00:04:27.830 --> 00:04:32.870
more, making your eyes look blue, unless,
of course, you have some melonen in that iris,

00:04:32.870 --> 00:04:37.330
in which case your eyes are going to be
green, hazel or brown.

